{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659775"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:14:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:14:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20898"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20898"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0.57,0.24,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13773"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97387"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13773"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20898"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80002"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"11801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12720"},{"type":"tags","id":"12721"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33199"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33200"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97387"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA couple has two children diagnosed with osteogenesis imperfecta, an autosomal dominant disorder. Both parents appear phenotypically normal with no clinical features of the condition. Genetic testing of the parents\u0027 blood samples shows no mutation in the genes associated with osteogenesis imperfecta.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains how phenotypically normal parents can have multiple children with this autosomal dominant disorder?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recessive inheritance pattern of the disorder","Mitochondrial inheritance of the disorder","Gonadal mosaicism in one parent","Incomplete penetrance of the mutation in the parents","Spontaneous identical mutations in both children"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGonadal mosaicism in one parent\u003C/strong\u003E best explains this scenario. Gonadal mosaicism occurs when a mutation arises during early embryonic development and affects only the cells destined to form the gonads. This results in a proportion of gametes (eggs or sperm) carrying the mutation while the somatic cells of the individual remain normal. A phenotypically normal parent with gonadal mosaicism can therefore transmit the disease-causing mutation to multiple offspring through their mutated gametes, despite showing no signs of the condition themselves and having normal genetic testing results from blood samples.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncomplete penetrance of the mutation in the parents\u003C/strong\u003E - If this were the case, the mutation would be detectable in the parents\u0027 blood samples, but they would simply not express the phenotype. However, genetic testing showed no mutation in the parents.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecessive inheritance pattern of the disorder\u003C/strong\u003E - Osteogenesis imperfecta is predominantly an autosomal dominant disorder. Even if it were recessive, both parents would need to be carriers, which would be detectable on genetic testing.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpontaneous identical mutations in both children\u003C/strong\u003E - The probability of the exact same spontaneous mutation occurring independently in two siblings is extremely low, making this an implausible explanation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitochondrial inheritance of the disorder\u003C/strong\u003E - Osteogenesis imperfecta is caused by mutations in genes encoding collagen proteins, which are nuclear genes, not mitochondrial. Additionally, mitochondrial disorders are maternally inherited, not from both parents.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe likelihood of multiple affected children in cases of gonadal mosaicism depends on the proportion of germ cells carrying the mutation in the affected parent.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gonadal mosaicism occurs when a mutation affects only cells destined to form the gonads, resulting in mutated gametes but normal somatic cells.","Gonadal mosaicism can explain how phenotypically normal parents can have multiple children with an autosomal dominant disorder.","The proportion of affected offspring depends on the percentage of germ cells carrying the mutation in the parent with gonadal mosaicism."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5; page 180."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80002"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20898"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80002"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T13:35:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T13:37:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13773"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97387"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroup